07882nam a22011055i 9783110435122DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104351227 a10.1515/97831104351222doi  a(DE-B1597)455580  a(OCoLC)1049626047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBL60 7aREL0040002bisacsh04a306.622300aSocial Imaginaries in a Globalizing World /ced. by Hans Alma, Guido Vanheeswijck. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (269 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Its Others : Studies in Religion, Nonreligion and Secularity ,x2330-6262 ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction to Social Imaginaries in a Globalizing World -- tSection 1: Social Imaginaries. A Historical and Conceptual Analysis -- tOn the Philosophical Genealogy of the Concept Social Imaginaries -- tSocial Imaginaries A Conceptual Analysis -- tRetrieving Realism in Social Imaginaries -- tSection 2: Social Imaginaries as Meaningful Spaces -- tContrast Experiences and Social Imaginaries as Spaces for Truth-Seeking -- tThe Play of the World Social Imaginaries as Transcending Spaces: From Taylor to Nietzsche -- t‘Plus de Biens’: Jacques Derrida and Charles Taylor -- tSection 3: Human Rights and Migration — (Post‐)Secular Social Imaginaries in Contemporary Perspective -- tStudying Culture through Imaginaries Some Reflections on the Relevance of Imaginaries for the Social Sciences -- tHuman Rights as a Secular Social Imaginary in the Field of Transitional Justice The Dutch-Indonesian ‘Rawagede Case’ -- tEurope and the Human Rights Imaginary The Role of Perceptions of Human Rights in Europe and Migration Aspirations -- tPost-Secular Nationalism The Dutch Turn to the Right & Cultural-Religious Reframing of Secularity -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow to study the contemporary dynamics between the religious, the nonreligious and the secular in a globalizing world? Obviously, their relationship is not an empirical datum, liable to the procedures of verification or of logical deduction. We are in need of alternative conceptual and methodological tools. This volume argues that the concept of ‘social imaginary’ as it is used by Charles Taylor, is of utmost importance as a methodological tool to understand these dynamics. The first section is dedicated to the conceptual clarification of Taylor's notion of social imaginaries both through a historical study of their genealogy and through conceptual analysis. In the second section, we clarify the relation of ‘social imaginaries’ to the concept of (religious) worldviewing, understood as a process of truth seeking. Furthermore, we discuss the practical usefulness of the concept of social imaginaries for cultural scientists, by focusing on the concept of human rights as a secular social imaginary. In the third and final section, we relate Taylor's view on the role of social imaginaries and the new paths it opens up for religious studies to other analyses of the secular-religious divide, as they nowadays mainly come to the fore in the debates on what is coined as the ‘post-secular.’  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGlobalizationxReligious aspects. 0aPostsecularism. 0aReligion and sociology. 4aCharles Taylor. 4aGlobalisierung. 4aSoziale Imaginäre. 4aWeltanschauung. 7aRELIGION / Atheism.2bisacsh  aCharles Taylor, worldviews, social imaginary, globalization.1 aAlma, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlma, Hans, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnbeek, Christa, econtributor.